###Research on Price data

Naming the price variables

GNI linear model by low GNI and high GNI (graph):

medianGNI <- median(merged_data_82$GNI_per_capita_2022)
merged_data_82$GNImedian <- ifelse(merged_data_82$GNI_per_capita_2022 < medianGNI, "GNI per capita < 15465", "GNI per capita 2022 > 15465")
ggplot(merged_data_82, aes(x = GNI_per_capita_2022, y = Cost_of_Living_Index, colour = GNImedian)) +
  geom_point() +
  ggtitle("Relationship between GNI per capita (lower and higher than median) and Cost of living index") + 
  xlab("GNI per capita") +
  ylab("Cost of living index") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", formula = y ~ x, se = FALSE)

Linear model, and calculating r-square:

m0GNI = lm(Cost_of_Living_Index~1, data=merged_data_82)
modelGNI = lm(Cost_of_Living_Index~GNI_per_capita_2022,data=merged_data_82)
modelGNI
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Cost_of_Living_Index ~ GNI_per_capita_2022, data = merged_data_82)
## 
## Coefficients:
##         (Intercept)  GNI_per_capita_2022  
##           3.098e+01            7.293e-04
residGNI = resid(modelGNI)
resid0GNI = resid(m0GNI)
R2GNI = (sum(resid0GNI^2) - sum(residGNI^2))/sum(resid0GNI^2)
R2GNI
## [1] 0.8578091

Single countries comparison:

sig_data <- c(2.56, 11.96, 18.67, 3.30, 2.95, 1.38, 2.09, 4.54)
mal_data <- c(1.15, 3.82, 12.29, 1.80, 1.53, 0.53, 0.81, 3.27)  
data <- data.frame(
  Compare = rep(c("Singapor", "Malaysia"), each = 8),
  Value = c(sig_data, mal_data),
  ID = c("rice", "cig", "cheese", "egg", "milk", "water", "bread", "beer")
)

ggplot(data, aes(x = factor(ID), y = Value, fill = Compare)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = position_dodge()) +
  labs(x = "Price of Products", y = "Value") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("green", "orange")) +
  ggtitle("Comparison of Data Provided by Singapore and Malaysia")
